ce:section.ce:para:
To assess the feasibility of the method for complex sample analysis, the fluorescence response of the Si QDs for K4[Fe(CN)6] in actual table salt and salted foods was investigated. As shown in Table 1
                        , the amounts of K4[Fe(CN)6] in some table salts including deep well rock salt, algae iodate salt with calcium contained, low sodium salt, rock salt, detected by the proposed method, were 6.02, 4.88, 5.65, 7.07 mg/kg, respectively, and the amounts of K4[Fe(CN)6] in this table salts also detected by national standard method, were 6.26, 4.92, 5.55, 6.81 mg/kg, respectively, which are lower than the maximum permitted residual amount internationally. Thus, these table salts are relatively safe. Meanwhile, the K4[Fe(CN)6] content in several salted foods was also determined (Table 2
                        ). The recoveries of this method were also studied in the samples by spiking a series of different concentrations of K4[Fe(CN)6]. The quantitative spike recoveries of this present method for the above real samples ranged from 91.90% to 107.00%, with a relative standard deviation of less than 7.00% (n = 3). Table 1 also presented the comparative analysis results for the K4[Fe(CN)6] obtained by the proposed method and those by national standard method, which showed our proposed method was accurate and was feasible and reliable for determination of K4[Fe(CN)6] in practical table salt and salted food samples.
